Experiment 3e
Title:Fetch and Render Data from a Public API using Axios in React JS
Aim: To develop a React JS application that fetches data from a public REST API using Axios and displays the data dynamically using React components.
Description: React JS is a component-based JavaScript library for building user interfaces.Each part of the UI (like a table, list, or form) is built as a component that can be reused.
1.	Component: A reusable piece of UI written as a JavaScript function that returns JSX.
2.	useState: React Hook used to create and manage state (data).
3.	useEffect: React Hook used to perform side effects (like API calls).
4.	Axios: A promise-based HTTP client used to fetch data from APIs.
Procedure:
1.	Create a React App (same as experiment 3c and 3d)
npx create-react-app fetch-api-demo
cd fetch-api-demo
2.	Install Axios
npm install axios in VS Code.
3.	Create and Edit Components
a.	Open src/App.js → main component
b.	Create a new file src/UserList.js → child component to display data
(After this just paste the code 4,5,6 step will happen automatically)
4.	Use useEffect() to call the API when the component loads.
5.	Use useState() to store and manage the fetched data.
6.	Render the fetched data inside the UserList component.
7.	Run the application: npm start
8.	Observe the output in your browser at http://localhost:3000


Source Code:

src/App.js
import React, { useEffect, useState } from "react";
import axios from "axios";
import UserList from "./UserList"; // Import child component

function App() {
const [users, setUsers] = useState([]); // State to store API data

  // useEffect to fetch data when component mounts
useEffect(() => {
axios
.get("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users")
.then((response) => {
setUsers(response.data); // Store API data in state
      })
.catch((error) => {
console.error("Error fetching data:", error);
      });
  }, []);

  return (
<div style={{ padding: "20px", fontFamily: "Arial" }}>
<h1>User Information</h1>
      {/* Pass data to child component */}
<UserList users={users} />
</div>
  );
}

export default App;


src/UserList.js:

import React from "react";

function UserList({ users }) {
  return (
<div>
<h2>Fetched Users</h2>
<table border="1" cellPadding="10" cellSpacing="0" style={{ width: "100%" }}>
<thead style={{ backgroundColor: "#f2f2f2" }}>
<tr>
<th>ID</th>
<th>Name</th>
<th>Email</th>
<th>City</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
          {users.map((user) => (
<tr key={user.id}>
<td>{user.id}</td>
<td>{user.name}</td>
<td>{user.email}</td>
<td>{user.address.city}</td>
</tr>
          ))}
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
  );
}

export default UserList;
Result
The React application successfully fetched and displayed user data from the public API using Axios.The output displayed a dynamic table containing User ID, Name, Email, and City.

